The paper discusses the use of robot learning from demonstration for human-robot collaboration tasks, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The paper also focuses on the communication aspect of human-robot collaboration, which suggests a potential fit for the human-computer interaction (cs.HC) category. Additionally, the paper discusses various machine learning techniques used in robot learning from demonstration, such as interactive/active learning and learning of complex tasks, which aligns with the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) categories. Finally, the paper discusses the design of collaborative robots, which could potentially fit under the systems and control (cs.SY) category.
